'''Reginald Abraham de Mel''' (8 November 1894 &ndash; 1961) was a [[Ceylonese]] politician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.lk/component/members/viewMember/2151?Itemid=206 |title=Hon. de Mel, Reginald Abraham, M.P.|publisher=[[Parliament of Sri Lanka]]|accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Members of the Legislatures of Ceylon: 1931-1972|author=Jātika Rājya Sabhāva. Pustakālaya|publisher=National State Assembly Library|date=1972|page=31}}</ref>

De Mel received his education at [[Richmond College, Galle|Richmond College]] in  [[Galle]], where he represented the college cricket team.<ref>[http://www.richmondcricket.lk/history.html History of Richmond Cricket Club] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504103232/http://www.richmondcricket.lk/history.html |date=4 May 2014 }}</ref> He served as the [[Mayor of Colombo]] from 1944 to 1946.<ref>[http://www.cmc.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=85&Itemid=71 Past Mayors of Colombo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820090238/http://www.cmc.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=85&Itemid=71 |date=20 August 2014 }}</ref>

De Mel was elected to [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|parliament]] at the [[1947 Ceylonese parliamentary election|1st parliamentary election]], representing the [[United National Party]] (UNP), in the [[Colombo South Electoral District|Colombo South electorate]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=University of Ceylon Review|date=1948|volume=6|publisher=[[University of Ceylon]]|page=169}}</ref> He secured 6,452 votes (35.4% of the total vote), 640 votes ahead of [[Paikiasothy Saravanamuttu]], an [[Independent politician|independent]] candidate, who received 32% of the total vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1947%20GENERAL%20ELECTION.PDF |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1947 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204000000/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1947%20GENERAL%20ELECTION.PDF |archivedate=2016-02-04 |df= }}</ref>
He was subsequently appointed the Deputy [[Speaker of the Parliament of Sri Lanka|Speaker]] and Chairman of Committees in the first parliament of Ceylon.<ref>[http://www.parliament.lk/en/deputy-speaker-and-chairman-of-committees Deputy Speaker and Chairman of Committees]</ref> De Mel subsequently lost his seat in August 1948 after being found guilty of corrupt practices by aiding, abetting, counselling and procuring the offences of impersonation.<ref name=ST280500>{{cite news|title=He gave of his best, but died a disillusioned man|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/000528/plus10.html|work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]]|date=28 May 2000|accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>

He was a cousin of [[R. S. F. de Mel]], former Mayor of Colombo.

